{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656487"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:14:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:14:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18742"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18742"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11474"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77296"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11474"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18742"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62803"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10186"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26568"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77296"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe inflammatory phase is the first stage of wound healing that occurs immediately following tissue injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic feature of the inflammatory phase of wound healing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wound contraction by myofibroblasts","Formation of granulation tissue","Collagen deposition by fibroblasts","Remodelling of extracellular matrix","Increased vascular permeability and neutrophil infiltration"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased vascular permeability and neutrophil infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E are hallmark features of the inflammatory phase. This phase begins immediately after injury and is characterised by vasodilation, increased blood flow, and the migration of inflammatory cells into the wound site. Neutrophils are the first cells to arrive, followed by macrophages within 48-72 hours.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent features of later wound healing phases:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of granulation tissue\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during the proliferative phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollagen deposition by fibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E is a key feature of the proliferative phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWound contraction by myofibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E happens during the later proliferative phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemodelling of extracellular matrix\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during the maturation phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe inflammatory phase typically lasts 3-5 days and is essential for preventing infection and initiating the wound healing cascade through the release of growth factors and chemokines.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The inflammatory phase of wound healing occurs immediately after injury and lasts approximately 3-5 days.","Neutrophils are the first inflammatory cells to arrive at the wound site, followed by macrophages.","Key signs of inflammation include redness, heat, swelling, and pain due to vasodilation and increased vascular permeability."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data